ce:section.ce:para:
Firstly, to facilitate effective excitation in SDT, sonosensitizers should not only possess narrow bandgap to drive the generation of electron − hole (e−–h+) pairs in low-intensity US settings, but also be capable of facilitating spatial separation of US-excited e−–h+ pairs to augment charge-carrier catalytic dynamics. On the basis of developing CoSnO3 nanocubes with narrow bandgap (1.6 eV), the construction of GQD/CoSnO3 heterojunctions displayed enhanced ROS production capability by virtue of the improved separation of electron-hole pairs, which was superior to various single-component sonosensitizers.[61–63] Secondly, because the adverse TME restriction (hypoxia and overexpressed GSH) severely restricts the therapeutic efficacy of SDT, sonosensitizers should be endowed with TME responses to relieve hypoxia and deplete GSH. The obtained CoSnO3 was discovered to demonstrate improved ROS generation efficiency due to its Co2+-mediated peroxidase (POD)-mimic catalytic activity, which produces cytotoxic OH, as well as its Sn4+-mediated glutathione-peroxidase (GSH-Px)-mimic catalytic activity, which consumes overexpressed GSH. In addition, the SDT performance of CoSnO3 would be enhanced via the CAT-mimic catalytic reaction to convert H2O2 into O2. Moreover, GQD/CoSnO3 heterojunctions exhibited amplified triple enzyme-mimic catalytic activities through the increased speed of carrier transfer. Therefore, the construction of GQD/CoSnO3 heterojunctions with synergistically enhanced sonodynamic performance and triple enzyme-mimic catalytic activity could realize cascaded amplification of ROS production, which was superior to a simple combination of two sonosensitizers and nanozymes that cannot generate a synergistic enhancement effect. Thirdly, although several heterojunction-based sonosensitizers such as Au-TiO2 
                     [64] have been explored for SDT or NCT, the lack of biodegradability could lead to the long-term safety concerns in future clinical applications. Herein, taking advantages of the pH-responsive biodegradability of CoSnO3 in weakly acidic TME, the tumor-specific GQD release was achieved for chemotherapy, in which GQDs could bypass multiple intracellular barriers and bind to the DNA major groove sites to induce topoisomerase I/II inhibition, DNA damage, and cell apoptosis based on our previous report [65]. Finally, owing to these favorable features, GQD/CoSnO3 heterojunctions achieved complete tumor eradication through the synergistic effect of chemotherapy, SDT, and NCT (Scheme 1
                     ).
